<h1>From Bryan Fairfax</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dear sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">[c.15 October 1769]</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I beg leave to trouble You with the inclosed two Letters; the one for Mr Pendleton has a little money in it including his Fee for his late advice, which I received yesterday, and which is expressed in these Words, I think you &amp; Colo. Washington should not pay the money for Mrs Savages separate use, to any person but by a power of attorney from her, especially as her changeable temper may subject you to danger in payments made upon her Letters.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-08-02-pb-0262">[262]</span>
<p>I forgot when I was last at Mt Vernon to inform you that there has been a trespass committed on yr Land by the Bridge, and I believe by a Man who a few weeks before carried the chain along the line and therefore cant plead ignorance. He has sawed up one of the finest trees, and if you pass it over you wont have a timber tree left in a few years. I believe I could fix it upon him if you desire it, as I hope you will.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>I dont know what to think of Frythe first Tryal I had of him, he, like Sr Francis Wronghead in the house of commons, did well enough upon the main, only he said ay when he shoud have said no:<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> that is, he insisted on it for one quarter of a mile that the back scent was the right one till the puppies that were with him refused to join any longer: and I think he did well enough upon the main as he &amp; four puppies killed the Fox, and was the leading dog the whole chace. The other time I have been out he never quitted the heels of the horses till the Fox was killed, but this seemed to proceed from his ignorance that any chace was going forward. I did not know when I accepted of your offer, that he was serviceable to any of your people in catching Racoonswould it be improper to write to Mr Stith to know whether he chooses the dog should be sent back to him, for if he does I will contrive him down to him.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0004-ptr">4</a></p>
<p>I had Capt. Poseys Advertisement put up at the Court House on tuesdaythe badness of the day on Monday prevented my getting to Leesburg till the next day.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0005" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> I am Dr Sir Yr most obedt hble Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Bryan Fairfax</p>
</div>
<div class="postscript">
 <p>For want of a little change I cant close my Letter to Mr Pendleton, and therefore, as I can do some other Business in Town, for I imagine the Court will not sit, I purpose down tomorrow, and will do myself the pleasure of being at Mt Vernon on tuesday night if you should not be engaged, and then I shall be glad to see the amount of the shingles We had for our Mill as Mr R &amp; I are settling our accounts.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0006" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0006-ptr">6</a> If you will be from home or otherwise busy on accot of your Journey please to let my man know it and I can send the letter down.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0181-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
 The docket, not in GWs hand, reads: without date.</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>The two letters have not been found. Edmund Pendleton was one of several lawyers GW used for his legal work. Bryan Fairfax wrote GW on 16
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-08-02-pb-0263">[263]</span>
April 1770 that Margaret Savage had sent Thomas Montgomerie her power of attorney dated 6 Oct. 1769. For a summary account of the Savage affair, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0342&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-07-02-0342-fn-0001#GEWN-02-07-02-0342-fn-0001" class="document">Henry Lee and Daniel Payne to GW, 24 April 1767, n.1</a>. See also <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-08-02-0080" class="document">GW to Margaret Savage, 28 June 1768</a>, and notes.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>The land that Fairfax is referring to is GWs Loudoun County land on Difficult Run, near Difficult Bridge. Fairfaxs home Towlston Grange was also on Difficult Run.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>Sir Francis Wronghead was a character in <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">The Provokd Husband</span> which Sir John Van Brugh (16641726) left uncompleted and Colley Cibber (16711757) finished. Cibber brought out the play in 1728.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0004">4</a>
 
   <p>Mr. Stith is probably John Stith (17251773) of the Chotank area of Virginia. GW had dinner with John Stith on 3 Sept. 1768 while visiting his brother Samuel Washington (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Donald Jackson and Dorothy Twohig, eds. &lt;i&gt;The Diaries of George Washington&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Charlottesville, Va., 197679. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Diaries</span></span>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-01-02-02-0003-0025" class="document">2:92</a>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>Leesburg is the county seat of Loudoun County. For John Poseys advertisement of his sale, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-08-02-0176&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-08-02-0176-fn-0001#GEWN-02-08-02-0176-fn-0001" class="document">GW to Hector Ross, 9 Oct. 1769, n.1</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0181-fn-0006">6</a>
 
   <p>The Loudoun County court met on the second Monday in each month; the October meeting would have been on the sixteenth. GW attended the Fairfax County court in Alexandria on 16 and 17 October. Bryan Fairfax came to Mount Vernon on 17 Oct., and he, GW, and Walter Magowan went fox hunting the next day. GWs account with Bryan Fairfax shows a charge of 22.15 on 21 June 1769 for 26 <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">M</span> Cyprus Shingles @ 17/6 (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Manuscript Ledger Book 1, 1750-72, in George Washington Papers, Library of Congress. ]">Ledger A</span>, 155). Mr R may be Joseph Ransom, who occasionally worked at Washingtons mill.</p>

</div>
</div>
